WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.200
I am pleased to introduce Colin Fay, over here, and Vincent Guider, who work at ThinkR,

00:00:13.200 --> 00:00:17.799
which is a R consulting services company based out of France, and they're going to talk about

00:00:17.799 --> 00:00:28.000
engineering production-grade shiny apps using golem.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:32.959
So, hi everyone, so my name is Vincent, this is Colin.

00:00:32.959 --> 00:00:38.480
We are both R hackers, and we love to do a lot of things with R.

00:00:38.480 --> 00:00:44.520
We work at ThinkR, ThinkR is a French company which works on everything R-related.

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:49.880
We do a lot of training, from beginner to expert, we do a lot of shiny applications,

00:00:49.880 --> 00:00:57.619
and we love to deploy these shiny applications in the real world, for the real customer needs.

00:00:57.619 --> 00:01:01.580
So we put R into production using shiny.

00:01:01.580 --> 00:01:07.260
And we are here today, we are glad to be here to present you a package called golem.

00:01:07.260 --> 00:01:13.599
So before going deeper into golem, I would like to talk about what is a prod-ready software.

00:01:13.599 --> 00:01:20.300
A prod-ready software should have metadata to know who to complain with, should be divided

00:01:20.300 --> 00:01:23.660
into chunks, into small functions.

00:01:23.660 --> 00:01:30.180
A prod-ready software needs to be tested, and you have to provide a list of requirements

00:01:30.180 --> 00:01:33.660
to help to deploy this application.

00:01:33.660 --> 00:01:40.820
And you have to document what you did in the software.

00:01:40.820 --> 00:01:41.820
Why do we need this?

00:01:41.820 --> 00:01:47.860
It is to be sure that this software will be good enough to go into production, and that

00:01:47.860 --> 00:01:52.860
this software will be good enough to be easily maintainable.

00:01:52.860 --> 00:02:00.260
So because if you have to create a shiny application, it could be really easy for everyone to create

00:02:00.260 --> 00:02:08.860
a quick shiny app, but if you want to create a real big shiny, it could be a mess.

00:02:08.860 --> 00:02:15.460
So you have to follow some rules, some steps, to be sure that the process will be okay to

00:02:15.460 --> 00:02:17.419
go into production at the end.

00:02:17.979 --> 00:02:24.179
And you want to follow rules to work with many people on the same project.

00:02:24.179 --> 00:02:31.139
So because if you want to put your little shiny app into production, you will have a

00:02:31.139 --> 00:02:39.660
lot of issues concerning velocity, security, and maintainability.

00:02:39.660 --> 00:02:41.339
So here comes golem.

00:02:41.339 --> 00:02:42.619
Golem is an R package.

00:02:42.660 --> 00:02:47.940
It's a framework which will help you to create a prod-ready shiny application.

00:02:47.940 --> 00:02:55.619
This package is for beginner, but also for experts.

00:02:55.619 --> 00:02:57.619
So what do you like the most?

00:02:57.619 --> 00:03:01.740
Okay, so let's start with this Q&A.

00:03:01.740 --> 00:03:03.860
What do you like the most?

00:03:03.860 --> 00:03:09.860
Work on building your data manipulation, visualization, and models, or spend 15 minutes checking that

00:03:09.899 --> 00:03:13.179
you've correctly copied and pasted shiny module skeletons.

00:03:13.179 --> 00:03:16.179
So who's A?

00:03:16.179 --> 00:03:19.179
Who's B?

00:03:19.179 --> 00:03:23.779
Oh, there's still some.

00:03:23.779 --> 00:03:31.539
So that's basically the idea behind golem, to provide a framework for doing all this

00:03:31.539 --> 00:03:39.020
automation, and if you are doing the same thing again and again and again, the best

00:03:39.059 --> 00:03:46.059
way to do it, and the best way to be sure not to mess up and not to have problems, is

00:03:46.059 --> 00:03:48.339
to use a framework.

00:03:48.339 --> 00:03:57.580
We can see it in many languages, even in R. Using a framework allows you to do things

00:03:57.580 --> 00:04:00.139
more secure.

00:04:00.139 --> 00:04:01.139
So why golem?

00:04:01.139 --> 00:04:05.699
You all know the idea that if you have to copy and paste a piece of code more than twice,

00:04:05.699 --> 00:04:10.139
you should write a function, and then if you have to copy and paste an infrastructure

00:04:10.139 --> 00:04:13.259
more than twice, you should write a framework.

00:04:13.259 --> 00:04:17.779
So that's basically the idea behind golem, is that we've been building a lot of shiny

00:04:17.779 --> 00:04:24.260
applications, but we've sent it to production, and in the beginning, it's just like you are

00:04:24.260 --> 00:04:28.779
building this application, then you are building a second one, and then a third one, and another

00:04:28.779 --> 00:04:34.500
one, but most of the things you do during the process can be automated, because it's

00:04:34.500 --> 00:04:41.380
very repetitive, it's some kind of things that you do again and again, so instead of

00:04:41.380 --> 00:04:46.140
having to copy and paste from an old shiny application into a new application, or instead

00:04:46.140 --> 00:04:54.140
of forgetting the steps, we have built golem, which is a framework for a shiny application

00:04:54.140 --> 00:05:00.140
that needs to be sent into production.

00:05:00.140 --> 00:05:02.100
So why are we using golem?

00:05:02.100 --> 00:05:07.820
Because we think that automation is gold, that is to say that if you have to do something

00:05:07.820 --> 00:05:12.579
again and again, it's better to automate it, so everything that can be automated should

00:05:12.579 --> 00:05:13.579
be automated.

00:05:13.579 --> 00:05:20.019
For example, the copy and pasting of a shiny module skeleton is an odd thing, because if

00:05:20.019 --> 00:05:24.700
you have to copy and paste from somewhere else, you can either have it, I don't know,

00:05:24.700 --> 00:05:29.179
on the web page, you can have it in another shiny application, you can have it into your

00:05:29.220 --> 00:05:36.260
notepad, and then just like copying and pasting it into your application, which is really

00:05:36.260 --> 00:05:41.940
subject to errors, because you can, you have to copy and paste something, and maybe you

00:05:41.940 --> 00:05:44.380
are missing a line, maybe something like that.

00:05:44.380 --> 00:05:53.220
So the idea is really these kind of things that can be automated should be automated.

00:05:53.260 --> 00:05:59.779
We also think that sharing is caring, so we made it open source because we try to give

00:05:59.779 --> 00:06:06.540
back to the community, so it's very important for us to share these good practices that

00:06:06.540 --> 00:06:12.700
we've been building for years, and it was important for us to open source this project,

00:06:12.700 --> 00:06:18.100
and also the idea behind this is to create some kind of collective intelligence, that

00:06:18.100 --> 00:06:25.100
is to say that if we are using it worldwide, that is to say that if a lot of people use

00:06:25.700 --> 00:06:31.220
the product, we can all build collective intelligence around it, that is to say, people are using

00:06:31.220 --> 00:06:38.100
it, they're giving feedback, they want to improve, and with Golem, it's these ideas

00:06:38.100 --> 00:06:44.980
to build collective intelligence around how to send shiny to production.

00:06:44.980 --> 00:06:53.540
So if we go back to what Vincent said about what is production-ready software, it has

00:06:53.540 --> 00:07:01.260
metadata, it is divided in function, it is tested, it lists the requirements, and it's

00:07:01.260 --> 00:07:02.260
documented.

00:07:02.260 --> 00:07:09.019
And if you think about it, this is what a R package is.

00:07:09.059 --> 00:07:15.779
So metadata are the description file, the functions are in the R folder, the tests are

00:07:15.779 --> 00:07:22.299
in the test folder, the requirements are in the namespace, and the documentation goes

00:07:22.299 --> 00:07:26.940
into the man and in the vignettes.

00:07:26.940 --> 00:07:31.899
So the big idea behind Golem, so the first and the central idea is that a shiny app should

00:07:31.899 --> 00:07:34.299
be a package.

00:07:34.500 --> 00:07:40.500
It's also very helpful to have a package structure if you want to talk with IT, because if you

00:07:40.500 --> 00:07:46.299
are sending just a file to your IT and say, hey, send it to production, and they are going

00:07:46.299 --> 00:07:50.459
to say, yeah, but which package do I need, do you have system requirements, where do

00:07:50.459 --> 00:07:54.220
you want to deploy it, how do you need things like that?

00:07:54.220 --> 00:07:59.579
But if you are sending a package, a package can be installed and install the dependencies

00:07:59.579 --> 00:08:04.980
and everything is documented, so it helps deploying the application, because everything

00:08:04.980 --> 00:08:05.980
is there.

00:08:05.980 --> 00:08:16.059
Also, with the documentation, with man and the vignettes, it helps to work on the project

00:08:16.059 --> 00:08:22.260
on the long run, because if someone comes and wants to take over the maintenance of

00:08:22.260 --> 00:08:27.420
your shiny application, you have everything documented with the package structure, and

00:08:27.420 --> 00:08:32.739
that also means that if you want to deploy it to your company, so if you want many users

00:08:32.739 --> 00:08:39.859
to use your application, you can install it as an R package and then they can do library

00:08:39.859 --> 00:08:47.659
your app and launch one function, but will not launch the application.

00:08:47.659 --> 00:08:52.619
And the cool thing is that everything you know about how to build a package, it will

00:08:52.619 --> 00:08:58.859
also work with Golem, so you don't have to learn something more if you know package development,

00:08:58.859 --> 00:09:04.979
everything you know about it will work, so we try to build on top of everything that

00:09:04.979 --> 00:09:12.580
exists and all the cool things like use this, like dev tools, like test that, so everything

00:09:12.580 --> 00:09:20.900
you know, everything that exists and works perfectly, we try to build on top of that.

00:09:20.900 --> 00:09:31.020
So this is the general idea of an application as a package.

00:09:31.020 --> 00:09:37.059
So how is a Golem composed?

00:09:37.059 --> 00:09:43.299
So if you start a new project with Golem, you're going to find this structure, so this

00:09:43.299 --> 00:09:50.780
is the structure for the upcoming Golem version, but you have standard things, so the description

00:09:50.780 --> 00:09:55.940
and the namespace and the man and the R folder, which are the standard thing that you have

00:09:55.940 --> 00:09:59.460
in a package.

00:09:59.460 --> 00:10:05.340
There is an app UI and app server, which are the shiny UI and the shiny server functions,

00:10:05.340 --> 00:10:09.820
so everything you have to put in your server goes there and everything that you have to

00:10:09.820 --> 00:10:15.500
put in your UI goes into UI, so UI server.

00:10:15.500 --> 00:10:23.780
The runapp.r file is used to launch your app and something that is coming in the next

00:10:23.780 --> 00:10:30.460
version of Golem is the use of the config package, so you have something called appconfig.r

00:10:30.460 --> 00:10:36.260
that handles the other files of the Golem config Yammer.

00:10:36.260 --> 00:10:45.940
So the inst and the man are standard package folders and the new thing is this dev folder,

00:10:45.940 --> 00:10:53.900
so the idea is that you have here four files, so the first is start, so it lists a series

00:10:53.900 --> 00:11:00.460
of steps you can follow to build your application, so the idea is that when you start your application,

00:11:00.460 --> 00:11:06.380
you have this start script that you can follow, so it lists a series of steps to follow and

00:11:06.380 --> 00:11:13.780
then you have dev.r file, which are a series of functions that you can call during the

00:11:13.780 --> 00:11:19.859
process of developing and you also have a deploy.r file that contains functions to create

00:11:19.859 --> 00:11:27.380
the deployment structures and the rundev is a script that you can launch to relaunch your

00:11:27.380 --> 00:11:30.099
application while you are developing.

00:11:30.099 --> 00:11:35.700
So the idea behind this dev folder is to be sure that you don't forget anything during

00:11:35.700 --> 00:11:42.659
the process, but it's also to be sure that you are documenting what you are doing while

00:11:42.659 --> 00:11:49.780
developing, so you will write everything that you are doing and you can keep track of what

00:11:49.780 --> 00:11:55.580
you have been doing and if you are working, like, with someone else, you can follow what

00:11:55.580 --> 00:11:58.140
they have done and you can see what they have done.

00:11:58.179 --> 00:12:01.340
So this is the idea behind the dev folder.

00:12:04.340 --> 00:12:10.500
I know that you said that, I told you that there would be automation, so I've been talking

00:12:10.500 --> 00:12:15.099
a lot about automation, automation, automation, so here comes the part about automation.

00:12:17.500 --> 00:12:25.299
We've tried to make it easy to do these repetitive things like creating a module, creating a

00:12:25.380 --> 00:12:32.380
CSS file, creating a JavaScript handler, using a favicon, so during the building process,

00:12:32.820 --> 00:12:38.460
if you want to add a new module, you have a function that says add module and what this

00:12:38.460 --> 00:12:43.219
function does is adding a module in the correct folder.

00:12:43.219 --> 00:12:50.859
Same goes for CSS, same goes for the JavaScript handler and the favicon, so if you build a

00:12:50.900 --> 00:12:57.900
large scale Shiny application, you might be using a lot of modules, so if you just add

00:12:58.580 --> 00:13:03.260
to copy and paste all the modules and T files, remove lines and things like that, it can

00:13:03.260 --> 00:13:09.299
get a little bit complicated, but with this function, you just have to give your module

00:13:09.299 --> 00:13:16.299
a name and it places the module in the correct folder, so all these repetitive things are

00:13:16.500 --> 00:13:22.580
easier and as they are automated, you are sure that you're not missing anything.

00:13:22.580 --> 00:13:29.340
Same goes for deployment, so if you want to deploy to any RStudio product, we have functions

00:13:29.340 --> 00:13:36.340
to create a file that can be deployed to connect to Shinyapps.io or to a Shiny server and if

00:13:39.099 --> 00:13:44.659
you want to create a Docker file out of your package, you also have free functions that

00:13:44.659 --> 00:13:49.739
can be used to create this Docker file and I hope that in the future we can support

00:13:49.739 --> 00:13:56.059
more deployment platforms.

00:13:56.059 --> 00:14:03.059
So for example, we have this template file for creating a module, so if I do golem add

00:14:05.500 --> 00:14:12.500
module and name, I name it my module, this will be create a file into R mod, so it will

00:14:13.500 --> 00:14:20.500
create a file in R which is called mod underscore my module dot R, so you don't have to provide

00:14:21.900 --> 00:14:27.820
the dot R, you can, but if ever you forget to, if ever you add it, it will be removed

00:14:27.820 --> 00:14:33.940
at the end of the file and if there is no dot R at the end, it will add it, so this

00:14:33.940 --> 00:14:40.940
kind of thing also helps you, you know, not having trouble copying and pasting things.

00:14:41.460 --> 00:14:48.460
So what this function does is creating this skeleton, so I removed the top part, but there

00:14:48.460 --> 00:14:55.460
are a series of Roxygen skeletons for documenting your module and the same thing that I said

00:14:56.979 --> 00:15:02.419
before is that you can have a hard time knowing where to put your modules and you have to

00:15:02.419 --> 00:15:09.419
think about IDs, about things like that and every module skeleton has this little part

00:15:11.099 --> 00:15:15.820
at the bottom that you can copy in your UI and you can copy in your server, so we are

00:15:15.820 --> 00:15:21.900
sure that the ID match and things like that, so you have this skeleton and you don't have

00:15:21.900 --> 00:15:28.460
to worry about whether or not you have the correct skeleton and whether or not you have

00:15:28.460 --> 00:15:34.500
the correct ID, they are just there because they are scripted and automated, so this is

00:15:34.500 --> 00:15:38.900
the ID behind add modules.

00:15:38.900 --> 00:15:45.900
What's next with Golem, so all the work in progress and all the IDs are listed on our

00:15:46.140 --> 00:15:52.140
GitHub repo, so if you want to contribute, you are very welcome to do so, so as I said

00:15:52.140 --> 00:15:57.979
before we are trying to build like a global intelligence around building Shiny applications

00:15:57.979 --> 00:16:04.260
for production, so if ever you have any ID or you want to contribute, all the work in

00:16:04.260 --> 00:16:11.219
progress and IDs are on our account.

00:16:11.219 --> 00:16:17.260
Also we, what's next is a new release of Golem, so I hope that it will be released in a few

00:16:17.260 --> 00:16:22.739
weeks, so we've been working a lot since the summer on a new version of Golem, so the Docker

00:16:22.739 --> 00:16:29.739
file creation is way more smart and is way quicker than before, we've been integrating

00:16:29.940 --> 00:16:36.940
the config.yaml, so the config package and future version of Golem, so this version will

00:16:37.700 --> 00:16:44.700
rely on using config.yaml, we've been working on the way it's documented, on the way module

00:16:45.460 --> 00:16:52.460
are created, and we've had more JavaScript internal functions, so we can hope that it

00:16:56.099 --> 00:17:01.820
will be released in a few weeks.

00:17:01.820 --> 00:17:05.420
What's next, what you can do is spread the word and share the stickers, so if you come

00:17:05.420 --> 00:17:11.939
to us, we have a series of, yeah, a handful of Golem stickers that we would be happy to

00:17:11.939 --> 00:17:15.979
share, so if you want to tweet, blog post, and talk to your friends and family about

00:17:15.979 --> 00:17:21.099
Golem, please do.

00:17:21.099 --> 00:17:26.339
So if you find a bug, if you want to give feedback, if you think, if you find something

00:17:26.339 --> 00:17:33.339
that you think is weird, you can open issues, if you have ID, feature requests, anything

00:17:34.660 --> 00:17:40.219
about Golem, I'd be happy to talk about it with you, and you can also open issues on

00:17:40.540 --> 00:17:43.339
the repo.

00:17:43.339 --> 00:17:50.339
So what's next is now it's way easier to send Shiny to production. We've also opened a new

00:17:53.579 --> 00:18:00.339
website called golemverse.org, so we are using this website to communicate about Golem, but

00:18:00.339 --> 00:18:06.619
also all the other package that gravitates around Golem, so we have another package called

00:18:06.619 --> 00:18:12.020
Shiny Zoom, we have things like that that are in the Golemverse, so everything around

00:18:12.020 --> 00:18:17.020
Golem will be listed here.

00:18:17.020 --> 00:18:23.060
And finally, we've been working on this book called Engineering Production Grade Shiny

00:18:23.060 --> 00:18:30.060
Apps, which is about how to build Shiny application for production, so it's not a book for beginners,

00:18:31.060 --> 00:18:38.060
it's more for people who have already a little bit of knowledge about Shiny and want to go

00:18:38.780 --> 00:18:45.780
a step further, so if you've heard about Mastering Shiny by Adly, it's just like a book that

00:18:47.780 --> 00:18:54.780
comes after that, I'd say.

00:18:55.780 --> 00:19:02.780
All right, we have time for a few questions, which I will read off of this slide.

00:19:06.699 --> 00:19:12.619
So our top question is, is Golem the right fit for all Shiny apps? Is there a rule for

00:19:12.619 --> 00:19:16.420
when a project is big enough to need the framework?

00:19:16.420 --> 00:19:23.420
Okay, so you can build any Shiny app with Golem, so even with a small one, I'd say that

00:19:25.780 --> 00:19:30.579
I think it's easier to start with Golem for a small Shiny app than starting a Shiny app

00:19:30.579 --> 00:19:36.459
then move to Golem, so if you think that at some point your Shiny application might grow,

00:19:36.459 --> 00:19:43.459
I think it's easier to start with Golem, and if you already have the templates, it's easier

00:19:43.459 --> 00:19:49.900
to continue and to build a larger app than to have the app and then turn it into a Golem

00:19:49.900 --> 00:19:50.900
application.

00:19:50.900 --> 00:19:57.900
All right, thanks. Our next question is, this is one I'm very interested in hearing

00:19:59.660 --> 00:20:03.739
the answer to, after developing and working with Golem in production, what have you learned

00:20:03.739 --> 00:20:08.739
about Shiny that you think needs to be improved to make it even better?

00:20:08.739 --> 00:20:15.739
Oh, a lot of things. That's a good one. I'm very looking forward for working with Shiny

00:20:20.900 --> 00:20:27.140
on asynchronous things in Shiny, so the Promises package. I know the current implementation

00:20:27.140 --> 00:20:33.739
is blocking for the user, but I know Joe has been providing some work around to use Promises

00:20:33.739 --> 00:20:38.180
and I think this is something that I'm very looking forward to, so better integration

00:20:38.180 --> 00:20:43.180
of asynchronous programming in Shiny.

00:20:43.180 --> 00:20:47.819
All right. With our Shiny server, we have problems with different Shiny apps requiring

00:20:47.819 --> 00:20:53.939
different package versions. How can Golem help us solve this?

00:20:53.939 --> 00:21:00.140
In every Golem package, you will have a description file containing every description you need.

00:21:00.140 --> 00:21:07.140
If you really use Shiny server, it will help you to install this package, but I think you

00:21:07.500 --> 00:21:14.060
have to provision to have different libpaths and so on to be sure to be able to run each

00:21:14.060 --> 00:21:21.060
Shiny application in different context, and Golem will definitely help you to do so.

00:21:22.060 --> 00:21:29.060
I think we have time for one more. Is converting a Shiny app into a package necessary or crucial

00:21:30.619 --> 00:21:37.619
to be production-ready? What is the main downside of not having it as a package?

00:21:38.619 --> 00:21:44.099
The main downside is that if you provide, so if you think of it as a package, it contains

00:21:44.099 --> 00:21:51.099
everything needed, so the dependencies and everything, so you can bundle it into a tarball

00:21:51.380 --> 00:21:56.819
and provide it to the IT and it works. You don't have to provide them the application

00:21:56.819 --> 00:22:03.540
and the requirements and everything, so as it's in a package, you can rely on the package

00:22:03.579 --> 00:22:10.579
structure to be tested, so we can use the tests, we can use the dependencies, features

00:22:11.060 --> 00:22:18.060
and everything that makes our package strength.

00:22:18.219 --> 00:22:21.619
Thank you very much, Colin and Vincent. Thanks for the talk.

